Description: The primary technical goal of the Metals Processing and Fabrication activity is to develop
affordable, robust manufacturing and repair processes/capabilities for metals and special materials critical
to Navy weapon system applications. Emphasis is on VIRGINIA Class submarine (VCS)/COLUMBIA Class
submarine (CLB), DDG 51 Class destroyer, CVN 78 Class carrier, F-35 Lightning II aircraft, and PEO IWS
systems.

Metals processing and fabrication technology areas include but are not limited to processing methods; metals
additive manufacturing; metallic materials-based systems; casting; joining techniques; machining; surface and
heat treatments; coating/cladding; assembly; metal/non-metals interfaces issues; and inspection and compliance
verification. Emphasis is placed on developing automated and robotic processes for the above.

For FY27, the sustainment manufacturing / Repair Technology (RepTech) portfolio is moving from the Metals
Processing and Fabrication activity to the Manufacturing Enterprise/Other activity.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Complete metals processing and fabrication projects in support of key platforms in areas such as inspection
technologies, robotics and automation, advanced welding technologies, and joining processes.
- Complete Repair Technology (RepTech) thrust to develop, optimize, and transition repair technologies for
key naval platforms at depots and logistics centers. At the project level, initiate approximately 3 projects in
sustainment technology once FY26 planning is complete.



