D. Acquisition Strategy
The GBASM concept started as an effort to conduct a live-fire, guided flight demonstration of ground based anti-ship capability to inform future requirements. The
program entered Milestone B in July 2021 and was designated ACAT III with a tailored MCA program. In October 2023, NMESIS was granted Milestone C and re-
designated as an ACAT II.

The NMESIS program leveraged a prototype development effort to integrate the existing Naval Strike Missile (NSM) onto a tele-operated Joint Light Tactical Vehicle
(JLTV) based launcher called the Remotely Operated Ground Unit for Expeditionary Fires (ROGUE-Fires), and develop/integrate the C2 and mobility control
components onto a separate manned command vehicle.

Other Transaction Authority (OTAs) agreements were used to develop the initial systems. Production contracts awarded beginning in FY 2022 covered the procurement
of systems for Initial Operational Test & Evaluation (IOT&E), Low-Rate Initial Production, Full Rate Production, Contractor Logistics Support and spares. Missile
procurement is accomplished via a Navy contract executed through the Navy Over-the-Horizon (OTH) Weapons Systems program office.

In conjunction with the Force Design Artillery Modernization plan, Medium Missile (MMSL) batteries will require an increase in capability to allow for future growth within
the MMSL batteries. These enhanced capabilities will be achieved through multiple communication, navigation, and product support ECPs. Central to these enhanced
capabilities is the requirement for one-to-many Fire Control and one-to-many Leader/Follower. Wireless fires and one-to-one Leader/Follower capabilities are being
fielded in FY 2026. Testing of one-to-many Leader/Follower will begin concurrently in FY 2026 with development continuing through FY 2028. One-to-many Fire Control
through Common C4 capability began development in FY 2025 and will be completed in FY 2027 with testing continuing into FY 2028.

Initial sustainment strategy reflects Contractor Logistics Support (CLS). Commonality with JLTV and OTH-WS components will support accelerated transition to primary
organic logistics support, augmented where necessary by CLS.




